{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.02,0.06,0.35,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88137"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72329"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"530"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43038"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88137"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-week history of pain in her right knee. Her symptoms start during her morning run and seem to be worse towards the front of the knee. It may also be aggravated when she has been sitting for a long time and suddenly stands up. The pain only settles after a period of rest or when she stretches her knee. She has no other joint symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. The knee joint looks normal, with a full range of movement. There are no points of tenderness, but the pain can be reproduced when the patient extends the knee against resistance. The rest of the examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prepatellar bursitis","Meniscal tear","Iliotibial band syndrome","Patellar tendonitis","Patellofemoral pain syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms of knee pain after exertion or prolonged sitting, aggravation of pain during tonic contraction of quadriceps (ie, extending knee against resistance), and normal physical findings are consistent with the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Epatellofemoral pain syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (PPS).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPPS is one of the most common causes of knee pain and is more commonly seen in females. Patients typically complain of knee pain after weight-bearing exercises or prolonged sitting. Physical examination may reveal crepitus when the knee is flexed. Patients may have increased pain when they are asked to extend the knee against resistance. Unlike a structural knee injury, patients do not have tenderness or erythema over the knee joint. Imaging is classically unremarkable. The diagnosis is primarily clinical. Management of PPS includes pain relief by NSAIDs and quadriceps strengthening exercises.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrepatellar bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by inflammation of the prepatellar bursa that is located anterior to the patella. It is also called housemaid\u0027s knee. It is caused by chronic stress or trauma to prepatellar bursitis and is associated with swelling anterior to the knee, erythema, limited range of motion, and tenderness over the swelling. This patient does not have an associated swelling and has a full range of motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniscal tear\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with joint line tenderness, swelling, and sometimes locking or clicking of the knee. This patient does not have these symptoms, making a meniscal tear unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliotibial band syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by lateral knee pain, often in runners, and is associated with tenderness over the lateral femoral condyle. This patient\u0027s pain is anterior, not lateral, making this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatellar tendonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with tenderness over the affected tendon and limited range of motion. In addition, patellar tendonitis pain is not localised to the front of the knee as seen in this patient. Patellar tendonitis pain is localised inferior to the patella over the patellar tendon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patellofemoral pain syndrome is the most common cause of non-traumatic knee pain in young, active adults.","The condition is often exacerbated by activities that put stress on the knee joint, such as running or prolonged sitting."],"references":["Petersen W, Ellermann A, G\u00f6sele-Koppenburg A, Best R, Rembitzki IV, Br\u00fcggemann GP, Liebau C. Patellofemoral pain syndrome. Knee Surg Sports Traumatol Arthrosc. 2014 Oct;22(10):2264-74. doi: 10.1007/s00167-013-2759-6. Epub 2013 Nov 13. PMID: 24221245; PMCID: PMC4169618.","Kasitinon D, Li WX, Wang EXS, Fredericson M. Physical Examination and Patellofemoral Pain Syndrome: an Updated Review. Curr Rev Musculoskelet Med. 2021 Dec;14(6):406-412. doi: 10.1007/s12178-021-09730-7. Epub 2021 Oct 29. PMID: 34713383; PMCID: PMC8733121. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8733121/","Manske RC, Davies GJ. EXAMINATION OF THE PATELLOFEMORAL JOINT. Int J Sports Phys Ther. 2016 Dec;11(6):831-853. PMID: 27904788; PMCID: PMC5095938. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5095938/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72329"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72329"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-02T10:31:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-02T10:35:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"790"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88137"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"s